'''''Baixing''''' ({{zh|c=[[Wikt:百|百]][[Wikt:姓|姓]]|p=bǎixìng|l=hundred surnames}} or '''''lao baixing''''' ({{zh|c=老百姓|l=old hundred surnames}}) is a term in Chinese meaning "the people", or "commoners".<ref>{{cite book|last= Lee|first= Philip |title=250 Essential Chinese Characters for Everyday Use|publisher=# Publisher: Periplus Editions (HK) Ltd. |date= June 2003 |pages=Page 25|isbn= 978-0-8048-3359-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XclXGDyToqoC&pg=PA25&dq=%22laobaixing%22&lr=&hl=zh-TW}}</ref> The word ''lao'' ({{zh|c=老|l=old}}) is often added before "baixing" to give the term a more affectionate tone.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}

Chinese family names are [[Patrilineality|patrilineal]], passed from father to children. Chinese women, after marriage, typically retain their birth surname. Historically, however, only Chinese men possessed ''xìng'' ({{zh|c=姓|l=family name}}), in addition to ''shì'' ({{zh|c=氏|l=clan}}); the women had only the latter, and took on their husband's ''xìng'' after marriage.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}

==Legendary origin==
{{tone|section|date=January 2015}}
{{See also|Yellow Emperor|Shennong|Chi You}}
{{clarify span|Thousands of years ago,|date=January 2015}} along the plain of the [[Yellow River]], there lived several large tribes, including the [[Yellow Emperor|Huangdi tribes]] ({{zh|c=黄帝族}}), [[Shennong|Yandi tribes]] ({{zh|c=炎帝族}}), [[Yi people|Yi tribes]] ({{zh|c=夷族}}), and the [[Jiuli tribe]]s ({{zh|c=九黎族}}). After {{clarify span|many years of tribal wars|date=January 2015}}, the [[Yellow Emperor|Huangdi tribes]], [[Shennong|Yandi tribes]] and the [[Yi people|Yi tribes]] formed an alliance which consisted of roughly 100 tribes, hence the origin of the Baixing {{zh|c=百姓}}, or the "hundred surnames". The three-tribe-alliance won the war over the Jiuli tribe, and the war captives became slaves of the alliance, hence the origin of the term Limin ({{zh|c=黎民}}), who were formerly of the Jiuli tribe.

==History==
During the [[Western Zhou]], Baixing came to mean "slaveowners" and Limin their slaves. {{clarify span|Over thousands of years|date=January 2015}}, the terms Baixing and Limin came to refer to the same thing, the common people.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}

