{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Bisweswar Bhattacharjee | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_date = 1942 | birth_place = [[West Bengal]], India | death_date = | death_place = | restingplace = | restingplacecoordinates = | othername = | occupation = Chemical Engineer | yearsactive = | known for = [[Gas centrifuge]] | spouse = | domesticpartner = | children = | parents = | website = | awards = [[Padma Shri]] }} '''Bisweswar Bhattacharjee''' is an Indian chemical engineer, multi-disciplinary scientist and a former director of the ''Chemical Engineering and Technology Group'' of the [[Bhabha Atomic Research Centre]] (BARC).<ref name="Shri B. Bhattacharjee Former Director, BARC">{{cite web | url=http://www.barc.gov.in/leaders/bb.html | title=Shri B. Bhattacharjee Former Director, BARC | publisher=Bhabha Atomic Research Centre | date=2015 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He is a former project director of the ''Rare Materials Project'', Mysore and a member of the [[Atomic Energy Commission of India]].<ref name="Zoom Info profile">{{cite web | url=http://www.zoominfo.com/p/Bisweswar-Bhattacharjee/81269112 | title=Zoom Info profile | publisher=Zoom Info | date=2015 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> Bhattacharjee, a recipient of the civilian honour of the [[Padma Shri]],<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web |url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df= }}</ref> is best known for his contributions in the development of [[Gas centrifuge|gas centrifugal technology]] for the High Speed Rotors (HSR), used in the production of [[enriched Uranium]] and other strategic materials, at BARC.<ref name="Shri B. Bhattacharjee Former Director, BARC" /><ref name="India's nuclear muscle : - BBC">{{cite web | url=http://www.oocities.org/bharatvarsha1947/Feb_2003/bbcnukes.htm | title=India's nuclear muscle : - BBC | publisher=Bharat Varsha | accessdate=11 January 2003}}</ref>
== Biography == Bhattacharjee was born in 1942 in the Indian state of [[West Bengal]] and joined [[Heritage Institute of Technology, Kolkata|University College of Technology, Kolkata]] to secure his master's degree in chemical engineering from there. Later, he joined BARC Training School to pass out in 1996.<ref name="Zoom Info profile" /> He served the [[Uranium Corporation of India]] at [[Jaduguda]], [[Bihar]], the only Uranium mill in the country and was instrumental in the establishment of the ''Rare Materials Plant'', a classified project in the Ratnahalli village of [[Mysore]].<ref name="BHATTACHARJEE IS BARC NEW CHIEF">{{cite web | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010404/nation.htm | title=BHATTACHARJEE IS BARC NEW CHIEF | publisher=Tribune | date=4 April 2001 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He has also been involved with the development of desalination plants for BARC; the plant attached to the [[Madras Atomic Power Station]], Kalpakkam is one of the fifteen plants supplied by BARC in the country.<ref name="New BARC chief assumes charge">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/2001/04/04/stories/0204000f.htm | title=New BARC chief assumes charge | publisher=The Hindu | date=4 April 2001 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He became the director of [[Bhabha Atomic Research Centre]] in 2001<ref name="New BARC chief assumes charge" /> and stayed at the post till 2004, handing over the charges to [[Srikumar Banerjee]] in April.<ref name="BARC GETS A NEW DIRECTOR">{{cite web | url=http://www.barc.gov.in/publications/nl/2004/200405-4.pdf | title=BARC GETS A NEW DIRECTOR | publisher=BARC | date=2004 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> It was during his tenure as the head of BARC, an accident occurred at the Kalpakkam reprocessing plant, on 21 January 2003, which caused exposure of six BARC personnel to radiation.<ref name="Barc admits radiation error">{{cite web | url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1030807/asp/nation/story_2241171.asp | title=Barc admits radiation error | publisher=The Telegraph | date=7 August 2003 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref>
Bhattacharjee is an elected Fellow of the [[Indian National Academy of Engineering]] (INAE)<ref name="Search Of Fellows">{{cite web | url=http://inae.in/search-of-fellows/ | title=Search Of Fellows | publisher=Indian National Academy of Engineering | date=2015 | accessdate=9 November 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403030936/http://inae.in/search-of-fellows/ | archive-date=3 April 2015 | dead-url=yes | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and a former member of the ''Nuclear and Radiological Emergency'' at the [[National Disaster Management Authority (India)|National Disaster Management Authority]].<ref name="Padmashree Shri B. Bhattacharya and former Director, Bhabha Atomic Research Centre inaugarates Seminar on Disaster Management at Kolkata">{{cite web | url=http://www.indiaprwire.com/pressrelease/education/2010022644470.htm | title=Padmashree Shri B. Bhattacharya and former Director, Bhabha Atomic Research Centre inaugarates Seminar on Disaster Management at Kolkata | publisher=India PRWire | date=27 February 2010 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He also sered as a member of the [[Atomic Energy Commission of India]].<ref name="Zoom Info profile" /> He has contributed the foreword to ''Chemical Metallurgy: Principles and Practice'', a text book on chemical metallurgy, published in 2006.<ref name="Chemical Metallurgy: Principles and Practice">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=Tq6MTFXk3cQC&pg=PR5&lpg=PR5&dq=B.+Bhattacharjee+BARC&source=bl&ots=p5vriuS0i8&sig=FoAdJPk-PnECe_Xs_sDgP7qn7wI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCWoVChMIxKa8hbeByQIViW0UCh1A-wau#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Chemical Metallurgy: Principles and Practice | publisher=John Wiley and Sons | author=Chiranjib Kumar Gupta | year=2006 | pages=831 | isbn=9783527605255}}</ref> The Government of India awarded him the fourth highest civilian award of the [[Padma Shri]], in 2001, for his services to the fields of science and engineering.<ref name="Padma Awards" />
