[[File:Ishinagenjo by Shigeru Mizuki, from his Yokai Encyclopedia.png|thumb|Ishinagenjo by [[Shigeru Mizuki|Mizuki Shigeru]]{{sfn|Mizuki|1994}}]]
'''Ishinagenjo''' ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: 石投げんじょ, "stone throwing ''genjo''") is a folkloric phenomenon which is documented to occur in the [[Nishisonogi District, Nagasaki|Nishisonogi district]] of the [[Nagasaki Prefecture]], the waters of [[Enoshima]], and the city of [[Tosu, Saga|Tosu]] in the [[Saga Prefecture]].{{sfn|Yanagita|1955|p=79}}{{sfn|Sakurada|1933|p=6}}

"In the month of May, the rainy season, a group of fishermen are working at night in the midst of a thick fog. Suddenly comes the sound of a huge rock crashing into the ocean, a tremendous splash and crack that sends the boat rocking and the sailors panicking. However, there is no rock to be seen, even by the break of day."{{sfn|Yanagita|1955|p=79}}

In the Japanese Folklore Institute's book ''Comprehensive Lexicon of Japanese Folklore'', the phenomenon is explained as being the doing of a sea monster - or ''[[Yōkai]]'' (Japanese: 妖怪, variously translated as "spectre", "monster", "goblin") - known as the Iso Woman, or some other related sea witch. This explanation is echoed in [[Kunio Yanagita|Kunio Yanagita's]] book ''Yōkai Lectures'', in which Yanagita concurs that the phenomenon is best explained by some oceanic ''Yōkai''.{{sfn|Yanagita|1977|p=201}} Because of this association, many experts have hypothesised that the "jo" - written in [[Hiragana]] as "じょ" - actually means woman - represented by the [[Kanji]] "女"{{sfn|Mizuki|1994|p=58}}{{sfn|Muramaki|2000|p=34}} - which is the rendering used by folklorist Sakurada Katsunori in her paper ''Ghost Ships and Drowning People''.{{sfn|Sakurada|1933|p=6}} Written thus, Ishinagenjo (石投女) translates literally to "stone-throwing woman". The [[Kojien]], on the other hand, renders "じょ" as "尉", meaning "captain" or "old man". The "stone-throwing old man" (石投尉) is likened in the text of the Kojien to an old man idly throwing stones into the sea.{{sfn|Shinmura|2008|p=147}} However, Yōkai expert Murakami Kenji has expressed doubts regarding the existence of any documentary evidence to visually identify the creature responsible for the phenomenon described.{{sfn|Muramaki|2000|p=34}} Indeed, the Kojien notes that it is assumed that fishermen only imagine seeing a monster, but that ultimately the experience as a whole is merely an illusion.{{sfn|Shinmura|2008|p=147}}

