{{Infobox person | name = Juri Camisasca | image = Juri Camisasca.jpg | image_size = | caption = Camisasca in 2017 | birth_name = Roberto Camisasca | birth_date = {{Birth-date and age|9 August 1951|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Melegnano]], [[Milan]], Italy | height = | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Singer-songwriter | spouse = }}'''Roberto Camisasca''' (born 9 August 1951), best known as '''Juri Camisasca''', is an Italian singer-songwriter and composer.
==Life and career == Born in [[Melegnano]], a self-taught musician, Camisasca debuted in 1974 with the [[progressive rock]] album ''La finestra dentro'', produced by [[Pino Massara]] and [[Franco Battiato]], which received large critical acclaim.<ref name="Deregibus">{{cite book|last=Enrico Deregibus|title=Dizionario completo della Canzone Italiana|publisher=Giunti Editore, 2010|pages=83–4|isbn=8809756258}}</ref> In the following years he collaborated as a vocalist and as a songwriter with Battiato and with other singers, and he took part to the musical project Telaio Magnetico.<ref name="Deregibus"/>
In 1979 Camisasca decided to enter a [[Benedictine monastery]], still keeping to be active as a songwriter for artists such as [[Milva]], [[Alice (singer)|Alice]] and [[Giuni Russo]].<ref name="Deregibus"/><ref name=music>{{cite book|last=Eddy Anselmi|title=Festival di Sanremo: almanacco illustrato della canzone italiana|publisher=Panini Comics, 2009|isbn=8863462291|page=622}}</ref> In 1987 he left the monastic life to embrace an [[Hermit|eremitical life]] at the slopes of [[Mount Etna]].<ref name="Deregibus"/> After participating to the Battiato's [[opera]] ''Genesi'' as a singer and as the narrating voice, he reprised his record activity in 1988 with the album ''Te Deum''.<ref name="Deregibus"/>
Camisasca is also active as an [[icon]] painter, an activity he gradually focused in later years.<ref name="Deregibus"/>
==Discography==
;Album * 1974 - ''La finestra dentro'' (Bla Bla, BBXL 10005) * 1988 - ''Te Deum ''(EMI, 66 791529 1) * 1991 - ''Il carmelo di Echt'' (EMI, 66 797202 1) * 1999 - ''Arcano Enigma'' (Mercury, 546 082-2) * 2016 - ''Spirituality'' (Warner Music, in couple with [[Rosario Di Bella]])
